In 1942, Miyazaki Naokatsu, governor of Chūreki District in [[Shinchiku Prefecture]], made the argument that Taiwanese mausoleums were Shinto, and when Taiwan became Japanese territory, Taiwanese ''[[kami]]'' became Japanese ''kami''..<ref name="shimizu-2022a" />{{rp|108}}
Tainan Shrine was built on the site of the death of Koxinga, a few blocks away from Koxinga Shrine.<ref name="shimizu-2022a" />{{rp|110}} It was unique in being granted permission to worship only the prince and no other deities, as almost all other shrines would worship the three pioneer kami too..<ref name="shimizu-2022a" />{{rp|112}}
In the 1960s, the shrine was converted back to a Confucian one.<ref name="crook-2019a" /> Similarly to the Japanese campaign, the [[:en:Kuomintang|Kuomintang]] government used the shrine as a way to legitimize its rule against the ascendant [[People's Republic of China]] across the [[Taiwan Strait]]<ref name="harrison-2016a">{{Cite book |last=Harrison |first=M. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZV3NCwAAQBAJ&dq=Koxinga+Shrine&pg=PA105 |title=Legitimacy, Meaning and Knowledge in the Making of Taiwanese Identity |date=2016-03-15 |publisher=Springer |isbn=978-0-230-60169-7 |language=en}}</ref> and was visited by [[:en:Chiang Kai-shek|Chiang Kai-shek]].<ref name="harrison-2016a" />
It shares this status with other converted Shinto shrines such as the [[National Revolutionary Martyrs' Shrine]] and many other [[:en:Martyrs' shrines (China)|martyrs' shrines]] in Taiwan.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Pan |first=Lu |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1rYREAAAQBAJ&dq=Koxinga+Shrine&pg=PA388 |title=image, Imagination and Imaginarium: Remapping World War II Monuments in Greater China |date=2021-01-02 |publisher=Springer Nature |isbn=978-981-15-9674-2 |language=en}}</ref>
