'''Koxinga Shrine''' ({{zh|t=延平郡王祠}}) is a Taiwanese historical temple originally known as '''Kaishan Temple''' ({{zh|t=開山王廟}}). It is located in {{ill|Tainan|en|Tainan|qid=Q140631|lt=Tainan|1=Tainan}}, {{ill|Taiwan|en|Taiwan|qid=Q865|lt=Taiwan|1=Taiwan}}.

==History==
Historical records show that a temple was originally built in the 17th century as a Chinese-style [[ancestral shrine]] in honor of Zheng's father {{ill|Koxinga|en|Koxinga|qid=Q197615|lt=Koxinga|1=Koxinga}}.<ref>{{Cite web |last=D |first=John |date=2016-10-02 |title=Koxinga Shrine in Taiwan |url=https://www.greenshinto.com/2016/10/02/koxinga-shrine-in-taiwan/ |access-date=2023-10-27 |website=Green Shinto |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Koxinga Shrine(延平郡王祠)-Cultural Affairs Bureau |first=Tainan City Government |date=2017-11-01 |title=Koxinga Shrine(延平郡王祠)-Cultural Affairs Bureau, Tainan City Government |url=http://historic.tainan.gov.tw/index.php?option=module&lang=en&task=pageinfo&id=207&index=6 |access-date=2023-10-27 |website=Koxinga Shrine(延平郡王祠)-Cultural Affairs Bureau, Tainan City Government}}</ref> However, other theories suggest it could be a temple worshipping [[:en:Wang Ye worship|Wang Ye]] or other folk heroes.

